Lectures that can be learned from today regarding the Cuban Crisis
"Thirteen Days" („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in the cinemas of many countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors in the White House.
Air photos of the region had revealed the construction of a missile base on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and those that could not be brought about, could have led to the outbreak of an atomic war.
The film illustrates what happened at the White House during these days.
Audio recordings made during President Kennedy's presidency played a significant role in the creation of the film.
Following the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion session to discuss both the film and the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this session included: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book on the "Kennedy-Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuba Crisis entitled "Essence of Decision" thirty years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film producer, was present.
Although the filmic adaptation of the theme was criticized at various points, the discussion participants could agree that the film portrays the problems and pressure President Kennedy was confronted with exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized it as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in case of a crisis, but ultimately it is the president who bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's clear analysis and his persistent questions were alternatives and dangers highlighted that were crucial in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; additionally, communication channels must remain open.
To put an opponent under pressure without keeping diplomatic channels open, which would allow for understanding their situation, could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted accordingly because the NATO, other Allies, and the opinion of the world supported him.
:: A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to rush them into action.
The fact that a week passed during which all relevant factors were examined and weighed to the utmost was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a time frame for deliberations still exist given the mass media landscape today?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the many criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade imposed by Kennedy on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's determination, and not as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the US had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
Doch Kennedy zeigte sich ängstlich in Bezug auf die Konsequenzen, die eine Stationierung sowjetischer Raketen auf Kuba hinsichtlich Berlin mit sich gebracht hätte.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which represented part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will be too late soon," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while they believed the missiles were en route by sea toward Cuba.
Eine etwa 180 000 Mann starke US-Truppe war auf eine Invasion vorbereitet; es gab sogar Pläne für ein Blitz-Bombardement, das in seinen Ausmaßen größer gewesen wäre, als der NATO-Angriff im Kosovo sechzig Jahre später. „Ich brauchte dreißig Jahre,“ so McNamara, „um herauszufinden, dass sich auf Kuba bereits Atomwaffen befunden haben: 162 Sprengköpfe, und davon 90 strategische Nuklearsprengköpfe.”
McNamara erhielt diese Informationen anlässlich eines Treffens mit Fidel Castro.
Er stellte Castro die drei folgenden Fragen: 1) Wussten Sie darüber Bescheid?
2) Wenn ja, was haben Sie empfohlen?
3) Was wären die Folgen für Kuba gewesen?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba."
Castro and, to a greater extent, his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba be reduced to ashes so that their country would become a martyr in the fight for world revolution!
An invasion might therefore have resulted in the deaths of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, merely because Kennedy's administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion "certainly" would have led to a Soviet atomic attack on the United States.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was limited: despite explicit contrary orders, U2 aircraft flying over Cuban airspace were shot down.
A difficult question that did not arise during the Harvard debate is this: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself more by rational behavior during the crisis, but someone like Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
In light of the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could become reality one day.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible yet entirely realistic idea.
Harvard has put a new website onto the internet, on which the key documents regarding the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org.
